text: "Which of the following hypothalamic nuclei are responsible for leptin resistance?",
options: [{"id": "A", "text": "Paraventricular nucleus", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "B", "text": "Lateral nucleus", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "C", "text": "Arcuate nucleus", "is_correct": true}, {"id": "D", "text": "Ventromedial nucleus", "is_correct": false}],
explanation: "Leptin resistance, a hallmark of obesity, develops at the level of the hypothalamic nucleus primarily responsible for integrating energy balance signals.<br><br>Why the arcuate nucleus is responsible:<br><br>* The **arcuate nucleus** contains the primary leptin-responsive neurons: the orexigenic **NPY/AgRP neurons** (which are normally inhibited by leptin) and the anorexigenic **POMC/CART neurons** (which are normally stimulated by leptin).\n* In obesity, chronic hyperleptinemia leads to **leptin resistance specifically at the arcuate nucleus**, often due to impaired leptin receptor signaling (e.g., via SOCS3-mediated negative feedback) and impaired leptin transport across the blood-brain barrier, blunting the normal appetite-suppressing response to elevated leptin levels.<br><br>Why other options are incorrect:<br><br>* Paraventricular nucleus: Receives output from arcuate nucleus neurons and integrates signals to regulate appetite and energy expenditure, but is not the primary site where leptin resistance develops.\n* Lateral nucleus (lateral hypothalamic area): Classically considered the 'hunger center,' promoting feeding behavior, but not the primary site of leptin resistance.\n* Ventromedial nucleus: Classically considered the 'satiety center,' but not the primary locus of leptin receptor resistance in obesity, which is centered on the arcuate nucleus.",
